01:16:07.620 --> 01:16:09.700
terrible political agendas.

01:16:09.700 --> 01:16:12.300
Think about Malthus in the 18th century.

01:16:12.300 --> 01:16:16.540
The reason that living standards will go back to subsistence is because population growth

01:16:16.540 --> 01:16:21.140
grows geometrically while food increases arithmetically.

01:16:21.140 --> 01:16:27.300
In the 1970s, there was a whole wave of ridiculous climate science championed by the Times, the

01:16:27.300 --> 01:16:29.980
New York Review, Columbia Brown.

01:16:29.980 --> 01:16:34.860
They were publishing articles about an inevitable ice age that just seems ludicrous from today's

01:16:34.860 --> 01:16:35.860
perspective.

01:16:35.860 --> 01:16:41.540
And of course, the terrors of the Nazis were justified on the latest science of the day,

01:16:41.780 --> 01:16:42.940
eugenics.

01:16:42.940 --> 01:16:48.620
Far from a pseudoscience, eugenics enjoyed enormous prestige in the early 20th century.

01:16:48.620 --> 01:16:54.220
It was grounded on Darwin, the latest evolutionary biology of the day, and responsible for the

01:16:54.220 --> 01:16:56.460
development of statistics.

01:16:56.460 --> 01:17:01.460
There was a University College London chair of eugenics in the same way there might be

01:17:01.460 --> 01:17:03.580
a chair for biology today.

01:17:03.580 --> 01:17:08.020
And eugenics was supported by Nobel laureates like Hermann Mueller and political leaders

01:17:08.020 --> 01:17:10.100
like Theodore Roosevelt.

01:17:10.100 --> 01:17:14.020
So I hope the problem of deifying science is clear.

01:17:14.020 --> 01:17:18.260
George thinks the reason that it is dangerous to deify science is the same reason it was

01:17:18.260 --> 01:17:21.820
dangerous to deify edicts of the Catholic Church.

01:17:21.820 --> 01:17:27.860
Just as the bloody European conquest of the Americas was, at least partially, legitimized

01:17:27.860 --> 01:17:33.620
through the appeal to Catholicism as spreading the gospel, today we too legitimize our often

01:17:33.700 --> 01:17:40.260
questionable political pursuits with just a sprinkle of reason, a little dab of science.

01:17:40.260 --> 01:17:44.660
And just as whomever used to disagree with the Catholic Church, we called heretics.

01:17:44.660 --> 01:17:50.900
We call those today who disagree with politically-charged, questionable science as anti-science, someone

01:17:50.900 --> 01:17:54.620
whose positions we don't even have to contend with.

01:17:54.620 --> 01:18:00.780
When deified, science becomes a blocker to truth and genuine inquiry, because it becomes

01:18:00.780 --> 01:18:02.780
a conversation stopper.

01:18:02.780 --> 01:18:05.660
Therein lies the hypocrisy.

01:18:05.660 --> 01:18:11.540
Now, the third force of Christianity is innovation, and it has been engendered by Christ in a

01:18:11.540 --> 01:18:14.500
very similar way that science was.

01:18:14.500 --> 01:18:20.380
By tearing down myths, we are freed from an exaggerated adulation of the past, and we

01:18:20.380 --> 01:18:24.740
are enabled and empowered to imagine its future.

01:18:24.740 --> 01:18:29.180
The idea that Gerard has in mind here might be better approximated by thinking about the

01:18:29.180 --> 01:18:30.420
negative case.

01:18:30.420 --> 01:18:35.740
What is certainly not conducive to innovation is the reactionary idea, not uncommon throughout

01:18:35.740 --> 01:18:41.100
most history, most famously perhaps among the Confucians and perhaps many Christians

01:18:41.100 --> 01:18:44.020
that our best days are behind us.

01:18:44.020 --> 01:18:50.340
And such a view lends to the practical orientation that the best we can do is to blindly imitate

01:18:50.340 --> 01:18:55.340
the past and press the brakes on the downward trajectory of history.

01:18:55.340 --> 01:19:01.180
Under such a worldview, the very word innovation had negative connotations in the West, up

01:19:01.180 --> 01:19:03.260
until the 18th century.

01:19:03.260 --> 01:19:09.100
Its connotations were negative because innovation implied a deviation from a sacred, albeit static

01:19:09.100 --> 01:19:13.500
and rigid ideal, provided to us by the myths of yore.

01:19:13.500 --> 01:19:17.420
Innovation before the 18th century was synonymous with heresy.

01:19:17.420 --> 01:19:23.060
Now, such an exaggerated respect of the past is often grounded on a religious belief in

01:19:23.100 --> 01:19:25.060
a mythologized past.

01:19:25.060 --> 01:19:30.140
Christianity frees us from this blind worship because it is a force, according to Gerard,

01:19:30.140 --> 01:19:34.460
of course, that tears down mythologization.

01:19:34.460 --> 01:19:39.380
It reveals to us what we once thought of as immutable, as arbitrary, so we are free to

01:19:39.380 --> 01:19:41.740
experiment and innovate.

01:19:41.740 --> 01:19:48.660
One of the surprising things that I've seen is this weird anti-correlation between mythologizing

01:19:48.660 --> 01:19:50.740
the past and innovation.

01:19:50.860 --> 01:19:55.020
I started to get this hunch when I would spend time around Silicon Valley types and

01:19:55.020 --> 01:19:59.820
you have dinner with them and they boast about their knowledge of the world.

01:19:59.820 --> 01:20:04.220
But then you start talking to them about the history of their own industry and it's not

01:20:04.220 --> 01:20:07.940
something that they think or talk about a lot.

01:20:07.940 --> 01:20:12.180
I compare that to the people I've met in the oil industry or the finance industry, these

01:20:12.180 --> 01:20:16.620
older and more established industries, where the people who I meet there, they know the

01:20:16.620 --> 01:20:19.020
history of their industries cold.

01:20:19.020 --> 01:20:20.020
You know what I mean?

01:20:20.300 --> 01:20:24.860
That's a very interesting observation that there is a negative correlation between how

01:20:24.860 --> 01:20:30.380
innovative an industry or a person is against how much they know about history or at least

01:20:30.380 --> 01:20:31.860
seem to respect it.

01:20:31.860 --> 01:20:36.620
I think Gerard would say that the difference between the tech industry and the oil industry

01:20:36.620 --> 01:20:43.340
is the same difference between modernity and pagan society, that we are much less idolatrous

01:20:43.340 --> 01:20:47.940
and concerned with the past and as a result much more oriented towards the future due

01:20:47.940 --> 01:20:49.940
to Christianity.

01:20:49.940 --> 01:20:56.300
Now, as we are freed from the grips of the past, innovation has brought about drastic

01:20:56.300 --> 01:20:57.860
technological and social change.

01:20:57.860 --> 01:21:01.620
Clearly, if you just look around our world, there's the mastery of travel and land, air

01:21:01.620 --> 01:21:02.620
and sea.

01:21:02.620 --> 01:21:07.420
There's the victory over disease and starvation, the political systems, gender norms, money,

01:21:07.420 --> 01:21:13.580
Western civilization, at least in the past few hundred years, is defined by and prides

01:21:13.580 --> 01:21:15.380
itself with change.

01:21:15.380 --> 01:21:20.580
The problem with innovation is the same problem with love and truth, hypocrisy.

01:21:20.580 --> 01:21:22.860
We've now fetishized innovation.

01:21:22.860 --> 01:21:25.160
We are conforming to contrarianism.

01:21:25.160 --> 01:21:29.140
We are obediently rallying under the banner of originality.

01:21:29.140 --> 01:21:33.060
Gerard has this to say, it's so good that I'll quote it in full.

01:21:33.060 --> 01:21:37.780
The modern world rejects imitation in favor of originality at all costs.

01:21:37.780 --> 01:21:40.740
You should never say what others are saying, never paint what others are painting, never

01:21:40.740 --> 01:21:43.300
think what others are thinking and so on.

01:21:43.300 --> 01:21:50.140
Since this is absolutely impossible, there soon emerges a negative imitation that sterilizes

01:21:50.140 --> 01:21:51.140
everything.

01:21:51.140 --> 01:21:57.100
More and more, often they're obliged to turn their coats inside out and with great fanfare

01:21:57.100 --> 01:22:02.780
announce some new epistemological rupture that is supposed to revolutionize the field

01:22:02.780 --> 01:22:04.460
from top to bottom.

01:22:04.460 --> 01:22:09.780
This rage for originality has produced a few rare masterpieces and quite a few rather

01:22:09.780 --> 01:22:11.100
bizarre things.

01:22:11.100 --> 01:22:15.380
The principle of originality at all costs leads to paralysis.

01:22:15.380 --> 01:22:21.500
The more we celebrate creative and enriching innovations, the fewer of them there are.

01:22:21.500 --> 01:22:27.100
For 2,000 years, the arts have been imitative and it's only in the 19th and 20th century

01:22:27.100 --> 01:22:29.980
that people started refusing to be mimetic.

01:22:29.980 --> 01:22:31.220
Why?

01:22:31.220 --> 01:22:33.660
Because we're more mimetic than ever.

01:22:33.660 --> 01:22:40.580
Rivalry plays a role such that we strive vainly to exercise imitation.

01:22:40.580 --> 01:22:45.700
The problem that Gerard is identifying here, with categorically rejecting imitation and

01:22:45.700 --> 01:22:52.420
idolizing innovation, is that imitation and meaningful innovation are often inseparable.

01:22:52.420 --> 01:22:57.560
You need to imitate and gain mastery first before you can make any real innovations.

01:22:57.560 --> 01:23:03.620
History is littered with examples where repetition, replication, imitation is a necessary precondition

01:23:03.620 --> 01:23:04.740
for innovation.

01:23:04.740 --> 01:23:10.220
Think about Goethe, who was a master of reproduction, reproducing the great poetic forms before

01:23:10.220 --> 01:23:11.660
he pioneered his own.

01:23:11.660 --> 01:23:17.100
Think about the industrial powers that started off as mere copycats but grew into innovators

01:23:17.100 --> 01:23:18.540
in their own right.

01:23:18.540 --> 01:23:21.060
Let me read Gerard again.

01:23:21.060 --> 01:23:25.860
It began with Germany, which, in the 19th century, was thought to be at most capable

01:23:25.860 --> 01:23:28.000
of imitating English.

01:23:28.000 --> 01:23:31.100
And this, at the precise moment, surpassed them.

01:23:31.100 --> 01:23:35.500
It continued with the Americans in whom, for a long time, the Europeans saw mediocre

01:23:35.500 --> 01:23:40.660
gadget makers, who weren't theoretical or cerebral enough to take on a world leadership

01:23:40.660 --> 01:23:41.660
role.

01:23:41.660 --> 01:23:46.140
And it happened once more with the Japanese, who, after World War II, were still seen as

01:23:46.140 --> 01:23:49.740
pathetic imitators of Western superiority.

01:23:49.740 --> 01:23:51.940
It's starting up again, it seems, with Korea.

01:23:51.940 --> 01:23:54.580
And soon, perhaps, it'll be the Chinese.

01:23:54.580 --> 01:23:59.260
All of these consecutive mistakes about the creative potential of imitation cannot be

01:23:59.260 --> 01:24:00.260
due to chance.

01:24:00.260 --> 01:24:01.260
End quote.

01:24:02.140 --> 01:24:07.380
Gerard's point here is that by fetishizing contrarianism, innovation, originality, and

01:24:07.380 --> 01:24:14.620
by rejecting repetition, replication, imitation, we paradoxically doom ourselves to never make

01:24:14.620 --> 01:24:20.820
any meaningful innovations whatsoever, because innovation is dependent on imitation.

01:24:20.820 --> 01:24:29.180
Now, as you can see, even the three quote-unquote good forces of modernity are deeply ambivalent.

01:24:29.180 --> 01:24:30.180
Nature's fundamentally changed.

01:24:30.180 --> 01:24:34.420
There's never been a society as loving, truthful, and innovative as ours.

01:24:34.420 --> 01:24:37.380
But stubborn human nature refuses to budge.

01:24:37.380 --> 01:24:41.300
We still need to persecute, to deify, and to conform.

01:24:41.300 --> 01:24:47.380
And so, the perversities of modernity for Gerard all take on the shape of hypocrisy,

01:24:47.380 --> 01:24:51.980
persecution under the banner of protecting victims, rigid adherence to scientific dogmas

01:24:51.980 --> 01:24:58.140
under the guise of free intellectual exploration, the most derivative of imitations packaged

01:24:58.140 --> 01:25:00.580
as radical innovations.

01:25:00.580 --> 01:25:06.340
The metaphor, then, that best captures this radical break as well as stubborn continuity

01:25:06.340 --> 01:25:10.500
is a just-launch rocket struggling to reach escape velocity.

01:25:10.500 --> 01:25:12.100
I mean, think about it.

01:25:12.100 --> 01:25:16.980
Such a rocket is clearly a radical break from it was stationary.

01:25:16.980 --> 01:25:22.260
But it is also in a continuity, because it is still governed by the pull of gravity.

01:25:22.260 --> 01:25:27.260
The same, perhaps, can be said for the point of history that we're in now.

01:25:27.260 --> 01:25:31.980
There's a clear radical break between our culture that protects victims and all the

01:25:31.980 --> 01:25:35.500
ones that have come before, which made them into scapegoats.

01:25:35.500 --> 01:25:40.260
But the stubborn gravitational pull of the human condition remains the same.

01:25:40.260 --> 01:25:44.260
We still need to persecute and find victims to blame.

01:25:44.260 --> 01:25:50.220
It's this tension between cultural advancement and the constancy of human nature that plagues

01:25:50.220 --> 01:25:52.260
modernity for Gerard.

01:25:52.260 --> 01:25:58.020
Now, our rocket ship of modernity is already in trouble, but the fourth and final force

01:25:58.020 --> 01:26:03.100
of Christianity will send it crashing towards the groundâviolence.

01:26:03.100 --> 01:26:07.780
You may be surprised that Gerard conceived of violence as one of the forces coming out

01:26:07.780 --> 01:26:10.860
of Christ's defeating the scapegoat mechanism.

01:26:10.860 --> 01:26:15.340
But given Gerard's understanding of how worldly peace is brought about, this conclusion

01:26:15.340 --> 01:26:18.700
in some sense should flow quite naturally.

01:26:18.700 --> 01:26:23.340
After all, if worldly order, a peaceful society, is founded on a deceitful, violent act of

01:26:23.340 --> 01:26:29.300
catharsis, then truth and love, which Christianity has unleashed, must be threatening if not

01:26:29.300 --> 01:26:31.620
harmful for this foundation.

01:26:31.620 --> 01:26:36.300
The scapegoat mechanism is a deeply morally ambivalent process for Gerard.

01:26:36.300 --> 01:26:41.460
It is deceitful, it is wrong, but it's also so damn effective.

01:26:41.460 --> 01:26:46.780
Just a single, innocent man has to be murdered for the entire community to be saved.

01:26:46.780 --> 01:26:50.900
Christ's one, for the peace of all, limits the freedom of the parts for the stability

01:26:50.900 --> 01:26:52.300
of the whole.

01:26:52.300 --> 01:26:57.460
And so, we might say, in a highly reductive fashion, that the scapegoat mechanism is a

01:26:57.460 --> 01:27:03.540
worldly good, but ultimate evil, whereas Christ is ultimately good, but brings forth worldly

01:27:03.540 --> 01:27:04.540
destruction.

01:27:04.540 --> 01:27:11.380
Gerard constantly reminds us that Christ himself says as much, Matthew 10.34, Christ

01:27:11.380 --> 01:27:13.380
has this to say.

01:27:13.380 --> 01:27:21.500
If not that I am come to send peace on earth, I came not to send peace, but a sword.

01:27:21.500 --> 01:27:26.740
Christ's sword is aimed at the scapegoat mechanism, which lies at the foundation of

01:27:26.740 --> 01:27:27.940
worldly order.

01:27:27.940 --> 01:27:33.940
Now, while the consequences of the Christian revelation for Gerard are violent and destructive,

01:27:33.940 --> 01:27:36.540
Christ's intentions surely are not.

01:27:36.540 --> 01:27:40.580
Christ did not cut down the worldly order for the sake of cutting down worldly order,

01:27:40.580 --> 01:27:46.860
but only so we may be freed from violence and lies, such that we can love each other.

01:27:46.860 --> 01:27:52.540
Christ took off our training wheels so that we may be freed, yet we've simply fallen

01:27:52.540 --> 01:27:54.660
and stumbled.

01:27:54.660 --> 01:27:59.700
Without the scapegoat mechanism, we no longer have our old prohibitions to stop metaphysical

01:27:59.700 --> 01:28:05.140
desires from running rampant, nor do we have sacrificial rituals to bring about catharsis.

01:28:05.140 --> 01:28:10.700
So to put it in other words, we've lost both our tools to prevent and resolve violence.

01:28:10.700 --> 01:28:13.020
So why haven't we gone bust yet?

01:28:13.020 --> 01:28:17.180
After all, the world looks pretty peaceful to me.

01:28:17.180 --> 01:28:23.380
Gerard responds, don't confuse the lack of the actuality of violence with the lack of

01:28:23.380 --> 01:28:25.740
the potential for violence.

01:28:25.740 --> 01:28:30.180
Violent energies have been building up and increasing, but they've been contained and

01:28:30.180 --> 01:28:36.460
productively channeled for now, by two new institutions of modernity.

01:28:36.460 --> 01:28:38.820
The first institution is capitalism.

01:28:38.820 --> 01:28:43.060
Capitalism is the channel that absorbs and productively directs violence.

01:28:43.060 --> 01:28:47.380
Let me be clear that when Gerard says that capitalism is a channel for violence, he

01:28:47.380 --> 01:28:53.620
doesn't have in mind whipping slaves to build the pyramids, but that the same violent, competitive

01:28:53.620 --> 01:28:59.380
energies of glory, of pride, of desire for conquest are the dominant ones driving capitalism

01:29:00.140 --> 01:29:00.620
today.

01:29:00.620 --> 01:29:07.220
Gerard reminds us, I quote, it is not by chance that the European aristocracy went into business

01:29:07.220 --> 01:29:11.140
once heroes and warriors went out of style, end quote.

01:29:11.140 --> 01:29:16.700
Gerard's point is that when we peek behind the motivational curtains of actors and capitalism,

01:29:16.700 --> 01:29:19.500
we shouldn't expect to find a desire to help others.

01:29:19.500 --> 01:29:23.980
We shouldn't even expect to find a materialistic greed, instead what people are really after

01:29:23.980 --> 01:29:28.940
are the same social goods, recognition, honor, prestige, glory.

01:29:28.940 --> 01:29:34.100
The princes and heroes of yore who would have amassed armies now find themselves competing

01:29:34.100 --> 01:29:36.700
to make products and services.

01:29:36.700 --> 01:29:42.420
Gerard warns us such, don't be fooled by the altruistic aims that capitalistic actors

01:29:42.420 --> 01:29:44.380
so desperately advertise.

01:29:44.380 --> 01:29:48.580
It's the same drive that drove Achilles to kill Hector, that drove Germany to invade

01:29:48.580 --> 01:29:55.180
France, that drove Caesar to capture Vercingetorix, that underpins our world economy today.

01:29:55.180 --> 01:30:00.300
It's funny, you're referencing ancient stories there, but even today, I'll look at my friends

01:30:00.300 --> 01:30:06.420
who are successful entrepreneurs and a shocking percentage of them were criminals in high school.

01:30:06.420 --> 01:30:06.940
Right.

01:30:06.940 --> 01:30:14.420
And I think that the same energy that drove them to be criminals, what capitalism does,

01:30:14.420 --> 01:30:18.380
is it redirects that energy towards entrepreneurship.

01:30:18.380 --> 01:30:24.100
Yeah, and I think this is both a deep critique of capital, right, that it's fundamentally

01:30:24.100 --> 01:30:30.940
driven off these spirited irrational forces, but also a depraise of capitalism, right?

01:30:30.940 --> 01:30:35.980
What a miracle it is today that people who seek revenge, who seek glory, who seek domination,

01:30:35.980 --> 01:30:42.100
who seek an outlet for their criminal energies have to do so, not by killing millions in

01:30:42.100 --> 01:30:48.180
zero-sum wars as people have done for thousands of years, but they have to compete in making

01:30:48.180 --> 01:30:51.060
better in products and services for others.

01:30:51.060 --> 01:30:55.940
What a miracle Gerard's analysis on capitalism is deeply ambivalent.

01:30:55.940 --> 01:31:00.700
Now, capitalism can only properly function in this way.

01:31:00.700 --> 01:31:06.700
When it is supported by law, law is the second important institution of modernity that contains

01:31:06.700 --> 01:31:08.140
violence.

01:31:08.140 --> 01:31:14.740
For Gerard, law only works in situations where there's an entity with a monopoly over violence

01:31:14.740 --> 01:31:17.980
that can arbitrate between disputing parties.

01:31:17.980 --> 01:31:24.020
Law does not bring about peace through catharsis, nor the edicts of law justified on the prestige

01:31:24.020 --> 01:31:25.340
of some deity.

01:31:25.340 --> 01:31:29.940
It keeps peace by threatening with you with more violence.

01:31:29.940 --> 01:31:36.360
If you, the injured party, aren't satisfied with the outcome of a trial and seek private

01:31:36.360 --> 01:31:41.480
vengeance by killing or hurting the criminal who injured you, then the state will come

01:31:41.480 --> 01:31:44.460
after you and punish you with more violence.

01:31:44.460 --> 01:31:49.700
Law only functions when there is such a powerful entity with a monopoly over violence that

01:31:49.700 --> 01:31:52.980
can easily overpower disputing parties.

01:31:52.980 --> 01:31:56.140
That's where its efficacy stems from.

01:31:56.140 --> 01:32:02.680
This is why within a single nation, laws are often inviolable and sacrosanct, yet between

01:32:02.680 --> 01:32:04.180
nations, right?

01:32:04.180 --> 01:32:08.340
Think the laws of the UN or the Geneva Convention.

01:32:08.340 --> 01:32:14.740
These laws without an entity, without a monopoly over violence, are so often transgressed with

01:32:14.740 --> 01:32:16.780
little consequence.

01:32:16.780 --> 01:32:22.200
For Gerard, capitalism is this bubbling stew of violent competitive energies that must

01:32:22.200 --> 01:32:27.180
be contained by law if that violence is not to overflow.

01:32:27.180 --> 01:32:33.800
That is why Gerard thinks the dyke will break where capitalism intersects the weakest points

01:32:33.800 --> 01:32:38.440
of law in between nations, in global trade.

01:32:38.440 --> 01:32:43.360
Global trade is where national pride and competitive energies are piled up, yet there

01:32:43.360 --> 01:32:50.280
is no monopolistic force of violence to arbitrate law between parties.

01:32:50.280 --> 01:32:55.900
Under this light, let me read you Gerard's startling predictions 15 years ago once more.

01:32:55.900 --> 01:33:01.360
He said this again at the height of Sino-American optimism, when popular wisdom all believed

01:33:01.440 --> 01:33:05.480
that relationships between China and the U.S. would only get better through trade.

01:33:05.480 --> 01:33:07.320
I quote to you again,

01:33:07.320 --> 01:33:11.160
A conflict between the United States and China will follow.

01:33:11.160 --> 01:33:12.800
Everything is in place.

01:33:12.800 --> 01:33:18.660
Though it will not necessarily occur on the military level at first, trade can transform

01:33:18.660 --> 01:33:20.720
very quickly into war.

01:33:20.720 --> 01:33:25.880
From this point of view, we can reasonably fear a major clash between China and the United

01:33:25.880 --> 01:33:28.320
States in the coming decades.

01:33:28.760 --> 01:33:32.600
If such a war between colossal nation states were to actually happen, it could very well

01:33:32.600 --> 01:33:34.600
be the last war.

01:33:34.600 --> 01:33:39.360
With the invention of nuclear weaponry, Gerard thinks we genuinely do live in an apocalyptic

01:33:39.360 --> 01:33:44.200
moment where the entire world can go up in flames in mere minutes.

01:33:44.200 --> 01:33:48.120
What is unique about the nuke isn't its singular destructive force.

01:33:48.120 --> 01:33:52.680
The firebombing of Tokyo, the Mongol mass murders, I think are all comparable to the

01:33:52.680 --> 01:33:56.080
devastation of a singular nuclear strike.

01:33:56.080 --> 01:34:01.640
What is unique about the nuke is that it forces rivals to utterly destroy each other at the

01:34:01.640 --> 01:34:04.160
first glimpse of provocation.

01:34:04.160 --> 01:34:09.000
Unlike firebombing or a Mongol horde that takes time to maneuver through terrain, there

01:34:09.000 --> 01:34:13.160
are no frictions to unleashing your entire nuclear arsenal.

01:34:13.160 --> 01:34:18.880
Before the nuke, nations fought wars like a boxing match, taking time to maneuver, resting

01:34:18.880 --> 01:34:23.880
in between with fatal blows rare and after taking a very long time.

01:34:23.880 --> 01:34:31.440
The nuke allows nation states to fight wars like a duel, an instant and fatal escalation.

01:34:31.440 --> 01:34:36.000
In many ways, it's worse than a duel because it allows the dead party to shoot the person

01:34:36.000 --> 01:34:37.480
who is alive.

01:34:37.480 --> 01:34:42.720
Even if you nuke my entire landmass into oblivion, my nuclear submarines can still avenge me

01:34:42.720 --> 01:34:44.280
post-mortem.

01:34:44.280 --> 01:34:48.920
This is what it means by mutually assured destruction.

01:34:48.920 --> 01:34:57.280
Armed in this light, Drard's worries of apocalypse is less theological speculation than deja vu.

01:34:57.280 --> 01:35:05.440
On October 27, 1962, a Soviet submarine armed with a nuclear-tipped torpedo was located and

01:35:05.440 --> 01:35:12.200
targeted by an American carrier group, dropping a signaling-depth charge like underwater bombs

01:35:12.200 --> 01:35:17.520
intended to destroy the submarine at the height of the Cuban missile crisis.

01:35:17.520 --> 01:35:22.320
The crew in that submarine had completely lost contact with Moscow for days and thought

01:35:22.320 --> 01:35:24.760
that a new world war had broken out.

01:35:24.760 --> 01:35:28.840
They were debating and considering whether to fire the nuke, believing that they were

01:35:28.840 --> 01:35:30.960
under direct attack.

01:35:30.960 --> 01:35:37.440
This submarine required all three senior officers to agree to launch the strike.

01:35:37.440 --> 01:35:40.520
Two of them decided to do so.

01:35:40.520 --> 01:35:47.120
Only one officer's stubborn refusal prevented an almost certain nuclear attack and likely

01:35:47.120 --> 01:35:48.560
Armageddon.

01:35:48.560 --> 01:35:50.400
This is how close we were.

01:35:50.400 --> 01:35:54.600
The will of one man was all that stood in the way.

01:35:54.600 --> 01:35:59.960
With the collapse of the Soviet Union, the specter of apocalypse has long faded from

01:35:59.960 --> 01:36:06.720
the public imagination, but Drard prophesies that this ghost of yours will soon return

01:36:06.720 --> 01:36:09.040
to haunt us once more.

01:36:09.040 --> 01:36:14.160
If the end of the world had a beginning, I think we could do far worse than attributing

01:36:14.160 --> 01:36:17.080
it to the invention of the nuclear bomb.

01:36:17.080 --> 01:36:20.640
So how ought one live in the end times?

01:36:20.640 --> 01:36:23.920
With apocalypse around the corner, what ought one do?

01:36:23.920 --> 01:36:27.920
Drard's answer is brief as it is unsatisfying.

01:36:27.920 --> 01:36:28.920
Withdraw.

01:36:28.920 --> 01:36:30.400
Withdraw from the world.

01:36:30.400 --> 01:36:31.640
Leave it all behind.

01:36:31.640 --> 01:36:32.880
Tend to your own garden.

01:36:32.880 --> 01:36:35.080
There's nothing you can do to stop apocalypse.

01:36:35.080 --> 01:36:38.440
You're only going to muddy your own moral character by trying to get involved in such

01:36:38.440 --> 01:36:39.440
a mess.

01:36:39.440 --> 01:36:40.440
Withdraw.

01:36:40.440 --> 01:36:43.920
Stay away from it all so that you can nurture your soul.

01:36:43.920 --> 01:36:49.200
The kingdom of God will not be established here on earth, but perhaps we can preserve

01:36:49.200 --> 01:36:53.080
ourselves to be worthy of it in heaven.

01:36:53.080 --> 01:36:59.560
On November 4th, 2015, Drard passed away peacefully in his home in Stanford, California

01:36:59.560 --> 01:37:06.960
at the age of 91, leaving us in deafening silence, stranded in an apocalyptic moment

01:37:06.960 --> 01:37:10.200
with nothing but the advice to withdraw.

01:37:10.200 --> 01:37:16.020
This is how Drard's story ends and where our lectures will also come to a screeching

01:37:16.020 --> 01:37:17.520
halt.

01:37:17.520 --> 01:37:22.640
Hopefully, I've given enough reason already to engage with Drard and continue with these

01:37:22.640 --> 01:37:23.640
lecture series.

01:37:23.640 --> 01:37:28.440
I fear that as time progresses, Drard will prove to be if you'll entertain another

01:37:28.440 --> 01:37:34.120
metaphor, a seismograph of history, able to feel the slight tremors that would balloon

01:37:34.120 --> 01:37:39.880
to tectonic shifts before others even know that we are standing on a fault line.

01:37:39.880 --> 01:37:43.240
Drard begins his final work as such.

01:37:43.240 --> 01:37:45.840
This is an apocalyptic book.

01:37:45.840 --> 01:37:51.840
It will become more understandable with time because, unquestionably, we are accelerating

01:37:51.840 --> 01:37:56.360
swiftly towards the destruction of the world."

01:37:56.360 --> 01:38:02.360
Unfortunately, his most unlikely prediction of worsening Sino-American relationships has

01:38:02.360 --> 01:38:06.280
already been made more understandable with time.

01:38:06.280 --> 01:38:11.680
On the topic of apocalypse, I desperately hope Drard is wrong, but I fear that he is

01:38:11.680 --> 01:38:13.160
right.

01:38:13.160 --> 01:38:17.680
If he is right, then Drard is worth engaging because he is one of the only guys to help

01:38:17.680 --> 01:38:23.920
us navigate the end time, one of the few Virgil's left who still take apocalypse literally

01:38:23.920 --> 01:38:25.560
and seriously.

01:38:25.560 --> 01:38:31.200
However, I would be a deceitful merchant of ideas if I also didn't share with you why

01:38:31.200 --> 01:38:35.400
you shouldn't engage with Drard or continue with these lectures.

01:38:35.440 --> 01:38:38.040
There's a common metaphor given about philosophy.

01:38:38.040 --> 01:38:42.200
Philosophy is often compared with medicine, that it has the power to cure our souls and

01:38:42.200 --> 01:38:47.600
societies and I think that's a quite apt metaphor, but just not taken far enough.

01:38:47.600 --> 01:38:51.280
Because just as medicine has side effects, so do philosophies.

01:38:51.280 --> 01:38:56.200
And I wish that philosophers wrote on the side of their books the unwanted side effects

01:38:56.200 --> 01:39:00.320
of their philosophies as pharmaceutical companies did it on their drugs.

01:39:00.320 --> 01:39:05.000
Warning, disdain for the material world if you take too much of these platonic dialogues

01:39:05.000 --> 01:39:06.320
in one sitting.

01:39:06.320 --> 01:39:11.160
Caution, more than one dose of Nietzsche a day makes patients with pre-existing health

01:39:11.160 --> 01:39:14.320
conditions descend into uncontrollable rage.

01:39:14.320 --> 01:39:18.760
Side effect, erectile dysfunction if you take these Buddhist sutras too seriously.

01:39:18.760 --> 01:39:25.280
Attention, inability to form coherent sentences if you read too much Adorno in one sitting.

01:39:25.280 --> 01:39:30.280
Just as a drug will course through your veins and infiltrate your entire system.

01:39:30.280 --> 01:39:35.440
Drard's ideas will latch themselves onto your psyche and colonize your world view.

01:39:35.440 --> 01:39:40.640
So we must ask, what are the side effects of engaging Drard?

01:39:40.640 --> 01:39:46.320
I've presented to you the red pill, but as any honest merchant I must also tell you why

01:39:46.320 --> 01:39:48.920
you should take the blue pill instead.

01:39:48.920 --> 01:39:53.520
The likely but not necessary side effects of Drard are threefold.

01:39:53.520 --> 01:39:55.720
First, alienation.

01:39:55.720 --> 01:40:01.360
Drard will likely show your most intimate long-held desires, ones that your entire identity

01:40:01.360 --> 01:40:04.960
have been staked on as external and alien.

01:40:04.960 --> 01:40:08.480
The career you've always wanted since you were four, the type of person you wanted to

01:40:08.480 --> 01:40:12.680
marry since childhood, the political cause that you've dedicated your life to, your

01:40:12.680 --> 01:40:19.280
core desires will likely be thoroughly alienated and shown to be external and perhaps even

01:40:19.280 --> 01:40:20.560
perverse.

01:40:20.560 --> 01:40:23.720
The medic theory could also alienate you from others.

01:40:23.720 --> 01:40:28.280
From this point going forward, you will have trouble fully participating in any political

01:40:28.280 --> 01:40:34.000
or collective activity, always aware of the deceitfulness of mimesis and the madness of

01:40:34.000 --> 01:40:35.000
crowds.

01:40:35.000 --> 01:40:37.480
Second, inaction.

01:40:37.480 --> 01:40:41.240
Drard is the most ambivalent writer that I've ever come across.

01:40:41.240 --> 01:40:43.400
What should we do with escape going?

01:40:43.400 --> 01:40:46.000
Well, on one hand, it's a huge lie.

01:40:46.000 --> 01:40:50.320
You're killing innocents, but on the other, it is the only way that pagan societies have

01:40:50.320 --> 01:40:51.320
brought peace.

01:40:52.040 --> 01:40:55.200
Should we fight to remove caste systems?

01:40:55.200 --> 01:41:00.480
Well, if you don't, then you will subject people to arbitrary distinction, meaningless

01:41:00.480 --> 01:41:02.800
oppression grounded on nothing but lies.

01:41:02.800 --> 01:41:07.400
But if you do, you open them up to competition of all against all.

01:41:07.400 --> 01:41:11.760
Metaphysical desire will burn through their communities and set it ablaze.

01:41:11.760 --> 01:41:14.760
Should we participate in capitalism?

01:41:14.760 --> 01:41:20.720
Capitalism is a competitive cesspool of violent energies that has brought about the most lovely

01:41:20.760 --> 01:41:24.000
prosperous and peaceful society known to date.

01:41:24.000 --> 01:41:27.800
If you are looking for clear-cut answers or even answers at all, you've come knocking

01:41:27.800 --> 01:41:28.800
on the wrong door.

01:41:28.800 --> 01:41:30.760
Go to a Marx or Hegel instead.

01:41:30.760 --> 01:41:36.840
The extreme ambivalence in all of Drard's ideas, in addition to his deep pessimism on

01:41:36.840 --> 01:41:42.800
the human condition and history, tends to incapacitate those who've digested them a

01:41:42.800 --> 01:41:44.520
bit too thoroughly.

01:41:44.600 --> 01:41:51.000
Third, and certainly not least, the side effect of Drard is hopelessness.

01:41:51.000 --> 01:41:54.680
By now, the point should be familiar.

01:41:54.680 --> 01:41:57.080
Apocalypse is imminent.

01:41:57.080 --> 01:42:02.840
There is nothing you, nor I, nor anyone can do about it.

01:42:02.840 --> 01:42:09.400
If you do wish to remain hopeful after understanding and digesting Drard, just know that that

01:42:09.400 --> 01:42:13.800
hope is going to have to come from you and not Drard.

01:42:13.800 --> 01:42:19.520
You are going to have to dig yourself and all of us out of this apocalyptic hole Drard

01:42:19.520 --> 01:42:24.800
really has nothing left to offer.

01:42:24.800 --> 01:42:27.280
Turn back while you still can.

01:42:27.280 --> 01:42:29.680
I have warned you thus.

01:42:29.680 --> 01:42:36.520
Now, to those stubborn or perhaps morbidly curious enough to continue, I can only heed

01:42:36.520 --> 01:42:43.640
one last time, against continuing on these lectures, by echoing what Dante inscribed

01:42:43.640 --> 01:42:48.360
on the gates of hell, abandon all hope, ye who enter here.

